title: adjust the quantization ops' definitions
body:
the PR contains,
1. Fix type constraints for QLinearConv (input. filter and output do not need to be same type though they're all 8-bit integers.
2. Add zero point as op input for ConvInteger and MatMulInteger.

The linear quantization math (zero_point/scale)'s math is,
r = (q-z)*s   -- r, s are floats, q, z are 8 bit integers.

so, the op design idea is, for matmul, there will be one op:
QLinearMatMul: q_y = (s_a*s_b)/s_y (q_a-z_a)(q_b-z_b) + z_y
s_a, s_b, s_y are floats;
q_a, z_a, q_b, z_b, q_y, z_y are 8 bit integers;

and one op:
MatMulInteger: q_y = (q_a-z_a)(q_b-z_b)
q_a, z_a, q_b, z_b are 8 bit integers;
q_z are 32 bit integers;

In this way, QLinearMatMul is actually be able to composed by MatMulInteger and some elementwise operators (Mul/Div/Add).

title: Build system upgrades
body:
1. Add a new cmake option:onnxruntime_BUILD_FOR_NATIVE_MACHINE. This should be enabled before doing any perf test on Linux.
2. Delete onnxruntime_CUDA_HOME cmake option. CUDA path and version will be controlled by standard cmake options.
3. Make onnxruntime_USE_OPENMP option switchable on Linux
4. Remove "find_package(CUDA)". We already have "enable_language(CUDA)". We only need one of them
5. fix some warnings in op kernels.
6. Move ONNX schema initialization from lazy-init to InitONNXEnv
7. Add --skip_submodule_sync to windows CI build pipelines
8. Upgrade cmake to 3.13. The next time, if anyone want to upgrade cmake, please change tools/ci_build/github/linux/docker/scripts/install_deps.sh and tools/ci_build/github/windows/download_cmake.py
9. Disable gcc's null pointer checker. Too many warnings
10.  Run the linux build as a non-root user.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
More words on the CUDA part:
There are two ways of enabling CUDA in cmake:  
1. "find_package(CUDA)", deprecated since cmake 3.10
2. "enable_language(CUDA)", available from cmake 3.8

And, old cmake can't work with newer CUDA version very well.  It's reasonable. It's like you can't expect a compiler release in 2014 has well support for c++17.  CUDA is changing, therefore we should get our cmake up to date.  And we will not try to support older cmake versions. Installing cmake is relatively easy. Based on that, for the two options in front of me,  I would choose the newer one.

However, the second one introduced a few problems. The biggest is, if you have code like:
```
string(APPEND CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS "-pthread")
```
You must change it to:
```
string(APPEND CMAKE_CXX_FLAGS "$<$<COMPILE_LANGUAGE:CUDA>:SHELL:-Xcompiler -pthread>"
            "$<$<NOT:$<COMPILE_LANGUAGE:CUDA>>:-pthread>"
```
And because of that, the most existing cmake modules are broken. If the code was written before cmake 3.8 was release, it's unlikely it can continue to work. Notably, FindThreads, googletest.

Let me talk them one by one.
On Linux, there are two compiler flags for enabling multiple threading. You can choose either of them.
1. '-pthread', could be apply to both compiling and linking
2. '-lpthread', linking only.
If I make the story shorter, the first one is deprecated, at least in the last 20 years, glibc doesn't need it. The second one is totaly enough. CMake FindThreads module has an option for choosing among them, but, its behavior is very strange and it doesn't always work.
If the cmake variable "CMAKE_THREAD_LIBS_INIT" is evaluated to '-pthread', it will break the CUDA build. Because nvcc can't understand this arg.  However, googletest explicitly says he prefer '-pthread' to '-lpthread'.  Nobody was wrong, expect cmake itself. The FindThreads module is updated in cmake 3.13 and this problem is fixed.

title: Use Eigen ThreadPool in OnnxRuntime
body:
This change does the following switches to Eigen Non Blocking Threadpool

1) for Windows over Windows Threadpool for better Thread lifetime management
2) for Linux/Mac over TaskThreadPool for performance and uniformity
3) In Test Runner to fix a bug where TLS memory leaks at test exit because of using Windows OS threadpool. (for the original issue look [here](https://github.com/Microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/261))

This change does not

1) Switch MLAS to use Eigen Threadpool - They still use Windows threadpool
2) Adapt/Extend/Wrap Eigen NonBlocking threadpool to better support exception propagation and work item completion signaling via packaged_tasks (eigen implementation only accepts std::function). Forking it in onnxruntime might mean we miss out on the maintenance goodness we get from Eigen team which is actively working on.

title: cuda fix to unblock the tf model tests
body:
Fix 2 issues:
1. conv cuda implementation not support symmetric padding, add code to fall back to cpu for this case.
2. fix random crash. 
    Root cause, the cast transformer may remove some node (type1 -> Cast -> type2 Cast->type1), the cast transformer is after the InsertCopyNode transformer, and the remove node causes the crash.
    Fix: the InsertCopyNode should be after all other graph transformer.

title: Handle copy to/from non-CPU devices across control flow nodes
body:
Control flow nodes only have CPU implementations, so if the input to the control flow node is on GPU, or the subgraph inputs/outputs are on GPU, we need to copy across devices.

This initial version will copy to everything to CPU to execute the control flow node, and copy to/from CPU to other devices as needed to execute the subgraph. It is not optimal, but will work. The next step will be to try and avoid those copies where possible but that will involve a much larger set of changes.

* Refactor the logic used by the main graph around copying inputs/outputs across devices so it can be re-used for subgraph execution
* Make code that creates mapping of inputs to devices aware of implicit inputs
* Update test infrastructure to be able to test a control flow operator which requires copy across devices

Most of the diffs are from moving code around.
